Usually algorithms can not be faster than *O(n)*, unless some work (like sorting, indexing, etc.) has already been done in advance (or is a precondition). This makes sense, since if the algorithm is faster than *O(n)*, it means part of the input, is not necessary.

We can for example make use of a `defaultdict` here, and then map the items to tuples:

    from collections import defaultdict
    
    tmp = defaultdict(list)
    for subl in (one_tup, two_tup):
        for k, v in subl:
            tmp[k].append(v)
    
    result = {k: tuple(v) for k, v in tmp.items()}

For the given sample data, this gives us:

    &gt;&gt;&gt; result
    {&#39;A&#39;: (1, 2), &#39;B&#39;: (2, 4), &#39;C&#39;: (3,), &#39;D&#39;: (4,)}

