The second argument passed to the `every` method off of the array is the `index`. You could check if the `index` is 0, and always return `true`. For example:

    [1, 0, 2, 3].every((elem, index) =&gt; { 
       if (index === 0) { 
         return true;
       } 
       return elem === 0; 
    }

In this way, the first element is never really considered in the truth test. 

https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/every#Parameters

